Description: Almost complete fragment of a seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration and partly a glossy surface. It also shows a blackened area, probably from fire. The rear shows a small area with wooden fibres, probably from a bolt or a box knob, roughly perpendicular to this two impressions of a turned cord with a width of approximately 0.25 cm. Another part of the rear is slightly concave in shape (from a knob?). The front side is convex and is covered in finger impressions. It shows an impression of a seal that seems to have been in the shape of a square cross with rounded ends. The motif shows a spiral pattern filling the complete seal.
Findspot: Excavated/Findspot: Amara West (Nubia), E14.7 temple magazine
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
